<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-701-110  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 701 110.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Computer Graphics and Applications  July 1990 v10 n4 p44(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>RenderMan: pursuing the future of graphics. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Apodaca, Anthony A.; Mantle, M.W.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The RenderMan Interface is a three-dimensional (3D)-descriptioninterface for realistic rendering of scenes and data.andP;  It isindependent of hardware platforms.andP;  It divides generating imagesinto modeling and rendering.andP;  The RenderMan Interface suppliescomplete definitions for all data that can be output as part of a3D scene description and permits the user to control the shadingprocess with four types of shaders: surface, displacement, light,and volume.andP;  RenderMan features include a comprehensivescene-description feature set, convex and concave polygons,polyhedral surfaces, bicubic patch, patch meshes, support forprocedural primitives, and support for all basic 3D graphicsfunctions.andP;  It includes support for transformation anddeformation, motion-blur, and camera.andP;  A complete RenderMan scenedescription can be contained in the RenderMan Interface Bytestreamprotocol.andP;  This is a complete transcription of the model.andP;  Over5,000 copies of RenderMan have been distributed.andP;  A number ofcomputer-aided design and product-design software suppliers areusing or plan to use RenderMan.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   RenderMan (Computer graphics software) (usage).andO;Topic:     Computer GraphicsCAD-CAMThree-Dimensional Graphics.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Modeling and rendering can be separated using the RenderManInterface. (chart)The state of the art in hardware advances, includingfunctionality. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>